sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE TAKE OVER THE TOP SPOT AFTER A FIRST INNINGS WIN.
West Indian all-rounder Phil Simmons hit four figures for 38 on Friday as Leicestershire beat Somerset by an innings and 39 runs in two days to take over the county championship lead.
Nonetheless, they may be short-lived as title rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey are all closing in on victory while Kent make up for lost time in their rain-affected match against Nottinghamshire.

After bowling Somerset out for 83 on the opening morning at Grace Road, Leicestershire extended their first innings by 94 runs before eventually being bowled out for 296 with England's discarded player Andy Caddick taking three for 83.
Trailing by 213, Somerset made a solid start to the second half before Simmons stepped in to bundle them out for 174.
However, Essex look certain to regain their top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such gave them a firm grip on their match against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, considered surplus to England's one-day requirements, scored 158, his first championship century of the season, as Essex reached 372 and took a first innings lead of 82.
By the close Yorkshire had turned it into a 37-run lead but off-spinner Such had dashed their hopes, taking four for 24 in 48 balls and leaving them hanging on 119 for five and praying for rain.

At the Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another man discarded by England, continued to silence his critics as he followed four for 45 on Thursday with 80 not out on Friday in a match against Warwickshire.
He was well supported by England-bound Mark Butcher, who made 70 as Surrey closed on 429 for seven, a lead of 234.
Derbyshire continued their hunt for their first title since 1936 by reducing Worcestershire to 133 for their second five overs, still 100 runs away from avoiding an innings defeat.
Australia's Tom Moody hit a six for 82 but Chris Adams, 123, and Tim O'Gorman, 109, took Derbyshire to 471 and a first innings lead of 233.
After the frustration of seeing their opening day of play severely affected by the weather, Kent stepped up to the plate to dismiss Nottinghamshire for 214.
They were held back by a hard-hitting 84 from Paul Johnson, but former England fast bowler Martin McCague hit four fours for 55.
By then Kent had reached 108 for three people.

FOOTBALL - SHEARER APPOINTED AS ENGLAND CAPTAIN.
The world's most expensive footballer, Alan Shearer, was named the new England captain on Friday.

The 26-year-old, who joined Newcastle for 15 million pounds sterling ($23.4 million), takes over from Tony Adams, who led the team during the European championship in June, and former captain David Platt.
Adams and Platt are both injured and will miss England's World Cup qualifier opener against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer took the captaincy on a trial basis, but new coach Glenn Hoddle says he sees no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton captain should not make the post his own.
"I'm sure there won't be any problems, I'm sure Alan is the right man for the job," Hoddle said.
"There are three or four people who can do it, but when I spoke to Alan, he was up for it and really wanted it.
"In four days it's very difficult to come to a 100 per cent conclusion about something like this....
but he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him and he knows about the team situation even though he plays up front. "
Shearer's Euro 96 partner, Teddy Sheringham, withdrew from the squad due to injury on Friday.
He may be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle team-mate Les Ferdinand.

FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS LOCKED IN AFTER VOLGOGRAD VIOLENCE.

Rotor Volgograd will have to play their next home match behind closed doors after fans threw bottles and stones at Dynamo Moscow players during Saturday's 1-0 home defeat that ended Rotor's brief spell as league leaders.
The head of the Russian league's disciplinary committee, Anatoly Gorokhovsky, said on Friday that Rotor will play Lada Togliatti in empty stands on 3 September.
The club, which knocked Manchester United out of the UEFA Cup last year, was fined $1,000.
Despite the loss, Rotor is in a good position with 11 matches left in the championship.
Three points behind Alania and two behind Dynamo Moscow, the Volgograd side have a game in hand on the leaders and two points on the Moscow club.
BOXING - ROBERTO DURAN OF PANAMA FIGHTS AGAINST THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Hands of Stone" Duran took to the ring on Saturday in another age-defying attempt to maintain his long career.
Duran, 45, faces little-known Mexican Ariel Cruz, 30, in a non-title super middleweight bout in Panama City.
This bout, which was Duran's first in his homeland for 10 years, was billed here as "The Return of the Legend", and Duran still spoke as if he was in his prime.
This match was to prepare me.
I'm not going to retire," Duran told Reuters.

But those close to the boxer admit that the man who has won championships in four different weight classes - lightweight, welterweight, junior middleweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"Every time he fights, he's on the last frontier of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could demean his position as one of the world's great boxers," said Panamanian Boxing Association President Ramon Manzanares.
Duran, whose 97-12 record spans three decades, hopes a win in this 10-round bout will earn him a rematch against Puerto Rican Hector "Macho" Camacho.
Camacho earned a controversial points decision against the Panamanian in Atlantic City in June in a title bout.

TENNIS - TARANGO, O'BRIEN SCORE TWIN WINS UNDER THE LIGHTS.
Andre Agassi escaped disaster on Thursday, but Wimbledon finalists MaliVai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky on a night filled with disappointment at the US Open.
The 11th seed Washington failed to repeat his comeback magic at Wimbledon as he lost to red-hot wildcard Alex O'Brien 6-3 6-4 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 in a two-hour 51-minute struggle on the Stadium court.
In the neighbouring stands, 10th seed Rios lost to another player with Wimbledon ties - bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The temperamental left-hander defeated the Chilean 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.
The day's programme was in full swing although sixth-seeded former champion Agassi had to dig himself out of a perilous 3-6 0-4 hole, winning 18 of the last 19 games against India's Leander Paes.
But the night belonged to the rookies.
Washington, who bounced back from a 1-5 deficit, trailing by two sets in the third against Todd Martin in the Wimbledon semi-finals, looked set for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, winner two weeks ago in New Haven of his first professional title, served for the match at 5-4 in the third set before Washington struck again.
"I just kept telling myself, 'keep giving yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting, maybe something will happen,'" said the 26-year-old O'Brien, who is ranked 65th.
"I kept my cool and I'm proud of myself for that - normally I would have folded up the tent and gone home."
The hard-serving O'Brien, a former US collegiate national champion, fired 17 aces to subdue Washington who never gave up.
The fifth set remained on serve until the sixth game, when Washington, after saving a break point with a forehand winner down the line, hit a backhand to give O'Brien a 4-2 lead.
The Texan served two aces to hold serve at 5-2 and then converted her eighth match point to clinch victory when Washington found the net with another backhand from 40-0.
"You just keep fighting and keep trying to get him to play a bit.
I think he was a little tense at some moments," Washington said."
But I think he served pretty well when he had to. "

Tarango, whose tantrum at Wimbledon two years ago saw him fined $28,000 and suspended from this year's tournament at the All-England Club, argued and taunted fans in a two-hour, 24-minute tango with Rios in the stands.
The cheering crowd supported the distracted Chilean and booed the lanky American, who commanded all the attention.
"I'm an emotional player," said Tarango, who is ranked 104th. "
I think I played very well tonight, very focused. "
The match came down to a third set tiebreak, which the American won 7-5, much to the disappointment of the crowd.
"I like the audience if they boo me every day.
It gets me excited, makes me play my best tennis," Tarango said.
"I played some of my best tennis in college when fraternities were throwing beer at me.
If tennis was like that every day, I think everyone would have more fun. "
Rios did not appreciate Tarango's antics.
"He always complains too much," Rios said. "
But I don't think that's it.
I think I played really badly.
It's very difficult to play at night.
I lost too many points that I never lost.
"I didn't see the ball like I did during the day.
I play as an American, so that's why I play at night.
I don't feel comfortable on the pitch. "
At the end of the bout, Tarango blew a sarcastic kiss to the crowd, and then wiggled his body toward Rios, who was cheering him on, as a salute.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango says of the fans. "
At the same time, they were openly cheering against me.
After I won, I thought I could give them a little excitement. "
Randall Cunningham, the National Football League's all-time great at quarterback and one of the most athletic players to ever line up at centre, retired on Thursday.
Cunningham played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
A three-time Pro Bowl selection, Cunningham rushed for 4,482 yards on 677 carries.
"I want to thank the Eagles organisation and the wonderful Philadelphia fans for supporting me throughout my career," Cunningham said.
"Although I feel sad to leave, I look forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that I have long since abandoned."
"Randall is one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," said Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie. "
During his 11 years in Philadelphia, Randall was a cornerstone of the Eagles franchise and brought many great moments to fans in Philadelphia as well as across the NFL. "
A second-round pick in 1985, Cunningham completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7 per cent) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham is already contracted as a broadcaster.
